Why RBAC Is Critical in ERP and Multi Companies Platforms
In an ERP or multi-company platform, the same login can sit behind wildly different stakes depending on which organisation it’s acting for, a warehouse clerk in one company shouldn’t be able to see another company’s invoices just because they share the same app instance, and a finance manager’s read access to payroll in their own org is a completely different thing from write access to someone else’s. RBAC matters here specifically because it turns “who can do what, in whose data” into a first-class, auditable concept instead of a scattering of checks buried across modules. With roles and permissions modeled as data, scoped per organisation, and enforced consistently at every entry point, adding a company, onboarding a new hire, or tightening what a role can touch becomes a configuration change instead of a code change
The DATA MODEL
Four entities carry the whole system:

• Organisation.

• Role.

• Permission

• OrganisationMembership
The organisation is the central unit that has data, it has an owner which is it’s creator, and memberhsips where memberships represent the user relation to an organisation, each membership has a user and a role and belongs to an organisation in that way we controll who see what.
To make the system more scalable I added permissions which represent small permissions given to the roles so that way we protect our endpoints with permissions that are general to the whole app, at the same time every organisation can create it’s own roles dynamically choosing who sees what, In that way the app is fully dynamic and each organisation is fully isolated.
One user can belong to different organisations using membership where a user can be an owner of an organisation and a limited member of another one.
The system role:
The system role is a general role that represents the admin, since permissions can change by the owners of the app(the whole app) how can we keep the admin having all the permissions?
I used a systemRole attribute which if set to true when the organisation is loaded all permissions are automatically granted to the role without having to be related to them in the database in that way no matter how the database change the admin will have access to everything in an organisation
Caching, and where invalidation gets sloppy
Permission checks run on every request that touches an authorized endpoint, so resolving a user’s permission set from three joined tables on every call is the kind of thing that looks fine in development and shows up in a profiler later.
The fix is straightforward: cache the resolved permission set per user per organisation, with a short TTL so a stale cache never lives long enough to matter on its own.
The part that’s easy to get wrong is invalidation. Since one role update in one organisation ends up wiping cached permissions for every user in every organisation. The more correct approach is to invalidate only what actually changed: when a role’s permission set is edited, that’s a change to the role itself, so it’s fair to clear broadly for that organisation; but when what changes is who wholds a role only a single membership being reassigned. The system should be able to tell the difference between “the role changed” and “one person’s role changed,” and invalidate accordingly instead of treating every write as a reason to flush everything.
Implementation
I implemented this twice, once in Spring Boot and once in NestJS, to see how the same model held up in two different ecosystems. The examples below are the Spring Boot version.
1- The core entities:
The role and membership model, stripped to what matters:
@Entity
public class Role { @Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
private String name;
private boolean isSystemRole;
@ManyToOne
private Organisation organisation;
@ManyToMany
private Set<Permission> permissions = new HashSet<>();
}
@Entity
public class OrganisationMembership { @Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
@ManyToOne
private User user;
@ManyToOne
private Organisation organisation;
@ManyToOne
private Role role;
}
2- The system role baypass:
This is what guarantees the admin always has full access, no matter what’s in the permissions table:
public Collection<Permission> getUserPermissions(String userEmail, Long organisationId) {
Role role = membershipRepository
.findByUserEmailAndOrganisationId(userEmail, organisationId)
.getRole(); return role.isSystemRole()
? permissionRepository.findAll()
: role.getPermissions();
}
3- The cache:
Resolving permissions on every request is expensive, so the result is cached and cleared broadly whenever a role is edited:
@Cacheable(cacheNames = "userPermissions", key = "#userEmail + ':' + #organisationId")
@CacheEvict(cacheNames = "userPermissions", allEntries = true)Wrapping up
That’s the core of it, roles and permissions modeled as data, scoped per organisation, with a system-role bypass so admins are never locked out and cache invalidation that doesn’t leak across tenants.
